            <commentid>9133</commentid>
            <who name="Christian Hagendorn">christian.hagendorn</who>
            <bug_when>2009-04-03 15:09:34 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Some demos have an German and English mix if the default browser language is German.

As example the widget~ColorPopup demo. The buttons from the application are in English, but the buttons from the ColorPopup are in German.
Other example is the widget~ColorSelector. The demo is shown completely in German.

Maybe there are more demos with an English and German mix.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>9516</commentid>
            <who name="Fabian Jakobs">fabian.jakobs</who>
            <bug_when>2009-04-23 11:14:24 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>The reason for this mix is that framework classes are translated but the demos are
usually only English. Since qooxdoo uses the browser&#39;s locale to translate the qooxdoo
classes you see German color popups.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>9554</commentid>
            <who name="Andreas Ecker">qooxdoo</who>
            <bug_when>2009-04-23 16:42:38 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Thanks Fabian for clarifying the technical reasons. Nevertheless I think we should address these inconsistencies as they make up for quite a bad UX.

Wouldn&#39;t it be best to include an explicit &quot;en&quot; locale switch for those demos (that are only available in English anyway), ignoring the user&#39;s settings?
</thetext>
          </long_desc>
